eCommerce Walkthrough: An Intro to Malloy Syntax & the VSCode Plugin

The following walk-through covers similar concepts to the Quick Start videos in the README. You can find the complete source code for this model here.

Malloy queries compile to SQL. As Malloy queries become more complex, the SQL complexity expands dramatically, while the Malloy query remains concise and easier to read.

Let’s illustrate this by asking a straightforward question of a simple ecommerce dataset--how many order items have we sold, broken down by their current status?

query: table('malloy-data.ecomm.order_items') -> {
  group_by: status
  aggregate: order_item_count is count()
}
QUERY RESULTS
statusorder_​item_​count
Complete243,032
Cancelled9,336
Returned2,537
Shipped1,792
Processing1,005
[
  {
    "status": "Complete",
    "order_item_count": 243032
  },
  {
    "status": "Cancelled",
    "order_item_count": 9336
  },
  {
    "status": "Returned",
    "order_item_count": 2537
  },
  {
    "status": "Shipped",
    "order_item_count": 1792
  },
  {
    "status": "Processing",
    "order_item_count": 1005
  }
]
SELECT 
   base.status as status,
   COUNT( 1) as order_item_count
FROM `malloy-data.ecomm.order_items` as base
GROUP BY 1
ORDER BY 2 desc

The use of group_by in the above query invokes a SELECT with a GROUP BY in SQL. Malloy also has a project transformation, which will SELECT without a GROUP BY.

Notice that after you write this, small "Run | Render" code lens will appear above the query. Run will show the JSON result, while Render will show a table by default, or a visualization if you've configured one (more on this later). Click the code lens to run the query. This will produce the following SQL:

SELECT
  base.status as status,
  COUNT( 1) as order_item_count
FROM malloy-data.ecomm.order_items as base
GROUP BY 1
ORDER BY 2 desc

Note: To see the SQL being generated by your query, open up a New Terminal in the top menu, then select Output, and pick “Malloy” from the menu on the right.

Next question: In 2020, how much did we sell to users in each state? This requires filtering to the year 2020, excluding cancelled and returned orders, as well as joining in the users table.

query: table('malloy-data.ecomm.order_items') {
  join_one: users is table('malloy-data.ecomm.users') on user_id = users.id
} -> {
  where:
    created_at ? @2020,
    status != 'Cancelled' & != 'Returned'
  group_by: users.state
  aggregate: total_sales is sale_price.sum()
}
QUERY RESULTS
statetotal_​sales
California$349,213.74
Texas$211,602.38
New York$140,235.20
Illinois$124,594.23
Florida$92,150.58
[
  {
    "state": "California",
    "total_sales": 349213.7414149046
  },
  {
    "state": "Texas",
    "total_sales": 211602.3806977272
  },
  {
    "state": "New York",
    "total_sales": 140235.2005108595
  },
  {
    "state": "Illinois",
    "total_sales": 124594.23045539856
  },
  {
    "state": "Florida",
    "total_sales": 92150.58025228977
  }
]
SELECT 
   users_0.state as state,
   COALESCE(SUM(base.sale_price),0) as total_sales
FROM `malloy-data.ecomm.order_items` as base
LEFT JOIN `malloy-data.ecomm.users` AS users_0
  ON base.user_id=users_0.id
WHERE ((base.created_at>=TIMESTAMP('2020-01-01', 'UTC'))and(base.created_at<TIMESTAMP('2021-01-01', 'UTC')))
AND ((COALESCE(NOT(base.status='Cancelled'),FALSE))and(COALESCE(NOT(base.status='Returned'),FALSE)))
GROUP BY 1
ORDER BY 2 desc

At this point we might notice we’re defining a few things we might like to re-use, so let’s add them to the model:

source: users is table('malloy-data.ecomm.users') {
  primary_key: id
}

source: order_items is table('malloy-data.ecomm.order_items') {
  primary_key: id
  join_one: users with user_id
  measure:
    total_sales is sale_price.sum()
    order_count is count(distinct order_id)
}

Having defined this in the model, the VSCode plugin will give us handy "Outline" and "Schema" tools in the left menu. "Outline" provides an interactive navigator of the model, in order, and "Schema" shows all of the attributes (both raw fields in the underlying table, and the dimensions, measures, and named queries you've defined in your model).

Our query is now very simple:

query: sales_by_state_2020 is order_items {where: created_at ? @2020} -> {
  group_by: users.state
  aggregate: total_sales
}

SELECT

GROUP BY 1
ORDER BY 2 desc

To further simplify, we can add this and a couple other queries we’ll frequently use to our model. Once you define these, the VSCode plugin will supply a “Run” button next to each query:

  query: sales_by_state_2020 is {
    where: created_at ? @2020
    group_by: users.state
    aggregate: total_sales
  }

  query: orders_by_status is {
    group_by: status
    aggregate: order_count
  }

  query: sales_by_month_2020 is {
    group_by: order_month is created_at.month
    aggregate: total_sales
  }

Allowing us to run the following very simple command next time we want to run any of these queries:

query: order_items -> sales_by_state_2020

Note that queries can be filtered at any level. A filter on a source applies to the whole source; one before the fields in a reduce or project transformation applies to that transformation; and one after an aggregate field applies to that aggregate only. See filters documentation for more information on filter expressions. Here's an example with a variety of filter usage:

query: order_items {
  where:
    users.state = 'California' | 'New York' | 'Texas',
    status != 'Cancelled' & != 'Processing'
} -> {
  group_by: users.state
  aggregate:
    total_sale_price_2020 is sale_price.sum() { where: created_at  ? @2020 },
    percent_items_returned is 100.0 * (count() { where: status = 'Returned' }) / count()
}
QUERY RESULTS
statetotal_​sale_​price_​2020percent_​items_​returned
California353,289.4110.983
Texas213,351.1611.016
New York141,933.3610.974
[
  {
    "state": "California",
    "total_sale_price_2020": 353289.41142356396,
    "percent_items_returned": 0.982545045045045
  },
  {
    "state": "Texas",
    "total_sale_price_2020": 213351.1607055664,
    "percent_items_returned": 1.016269860203254
  },
  {
    "state": "New York",
    "total_sale_price_2020": 141933.36051499844,
    "percent_items_returned": 0.9740947271828898
  }
]
SELECT 
   users_0.state as state,
   COALESCE(SUM(CASE WHEN (order_items.created_at>=TIMESTAMP('2020-01-01', 'UTC'))and(order_items.created_at<TIMESTAMP('2021-01-01', 'UTC')) THEN order_items.sale_price END),0) as total_sale_price_2020,
   100.0*COUNT( CASE WHEN order_items.status='Returned' THEN 1 END)/COUNT( 1) as percent_items_returned
FROM `malloy-data.ecomm.order_items` as order_items
LEFT JOIN `malloy-data.ecomm.users` AS users_0
  ON users_0.id=order_items.user_id
WHERE ((users_0.state='California')or((users_0.state='New York')or(users_0.state='Texas')))
AND ((COALESCE(NOT(order_items.status='Cancelled'),FALSE))and(COALESCE(NOT(order_items.status='Processing'),FALSE)))
GROUP BY 1
ORDER BY 2 desc

Queries can contain other nested structures, by including additional transformations as fields, so our named query (sales_by_month_2020) can also now be called anywhere as a nested structure. Note that these structures can nest infinitely!:

query: order_items -> {
  group_by: users.state
  aggregate: total_sales
  nest:
    orders_by_status
    sales_by_month_2020
}

WITH __stage0 AS (
  SELECT
    group_set,
    CASE WHEN group_set IN (0,1,2) THEN
      users_0.state
      END as state__0,
    CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(order_items.sale_price),0)
      END as total_sales__0,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      order_items.status
      END as status__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      count(distinct order_items.order_id)
      END as order_count__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=2 THEN
      TIMESTAMP_TRUNC(order_items.created_at,month)
      END as order_month__2,
    CASE WHEN group_set=2 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(order_items.sale_price),0)
      END as total_sales__2
  FROM `malloy-data.ecomm.order_items` as order_items
  LEFT JOIN `malloy-data.ecomm.users` AS users_0
    ON users_0.id=order_items.user_id
  CROSS JOIN (SELECT row_number() OVER() -1  group_set FROM UNNEST(GENERATE_ARRAY(0,2,1)))
  WHERE (group_set NOT IN (2) OR (group_set IN (2) AND (order_items.created_at>=TIMESTAMP('2020-01-01', 'UTC'))and(order_items.created_at<TIMESTAMP('2021-01-01', 'UTC'))))
  GROUP BY 1,2,4,6
)
SELECT
  state__0 as state,
  ANY_VALUE(CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN total_sales__0 END) as total_sales,
  ARRAY_AGG(CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN STRUCT(
    status__1 as status, 
    order_count__1 as order_count
    ) END IGNORE NULLS  ORDER BY  order_count__1 desc ) as orders_by_status,
  ARRAY_AGG(CASE WHEN group_set=2 THEN STRUCT(
    order_month__2 as order_month, 
    total_sales__2 as total_sales
    ) END IGNORE NULLS  ORDER BY  order_month__2 desc ) as sales_by_month_2020
FROM __stage0
GROUP BY 1
ORDER BY 2 desc

{
  "sales_by_month_2020": {
    "renderer": "line_chart"
  },
  "orders_by_status": {
    "renderer": "bar_chart"
  }
}

Putting a few named queries together as nested structures allows us to produce a dashboard with an overview of sales, having written remarkably little code. Use the dashboard renderer to format the results like this:

query: state_dashboard is order_items -> {
  group_by: users.state
  aggregate:
    total_sales
    order_count
  nest:
    orders_by_status
    sales_by_month_2020
}

WITH __stage0 AS (
  SELECT
    group_set,
    CASE WHEN group_set IN (0,1,2) THEN
      users_0.state
      END as state__0,
    CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(order_items.sale_price),0)
      END as total_sales__0,
    CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN
      count(distinct order_items.order_id)
      END as order_count__0,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      order_items.status
      END as status__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN
      count(distinct order_items.order_id)
      END as order_count__1,
    CASE WHEN group_set=2 THEN
      TIMESTAMP_TRUNC(order_items.created_at,month)
      END as order_month__2,
    CASE WHEN group_set=2 THEN
      COALESCE(SUM(order_items.sale_price),0)
      END as total_sales__2
  FROM `malloy-data.ecomm.order_items` as order_items
  LEFT JOIN `malloy-data.ecomm.users` AS users_0
    ON users_0.id=order_items.user_id
  CROSS JOIN (SELECT row_number() OVER() -1  group_set FROM UNNEST(GENERATE_ARRAY(0,2,1)))
  WHERE (group_set NOT IN (2) OR (group_set IN (2) AND (order_items.created_at>=TIMESTAMP('2020-01-01', 'UTC'))and(order_items.created_at<TIMESTAMP('2021-01-01', 'UTC'))))
  GROUP BY 1,2,5,7
)
SELECT
  state__0 as state,
  ANY_VALUE(CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN total_sales__0 END) as total_sales,
  ANY_VALUE(CASE WHEN group_set=0 THEN order_count__0 END) as order_count,
  ARRAY_AGG(CASE WHEN group_set=1 THEN STRUCT(
    status__1 as status, 
    order_count__1 as order_count
    ) END IGNORE NULLS  ORDER BY  order_count__1 desc ) as orders_by_status,
  ARRAY_AGG(CASE WHEN group_set=2 THEN STRUCT(
    order_month__2 as order_month, 
    total_sales__2 as total_sales
    ) END IGNORE NULLS  ORDER BY  order_month__2 desc ) as sales_by_month_2020
FROM __stage0
GROUP BY 1
ORDER BY 2 desc
